5000|$|Although Isidore {{taught in}} the Etymologiae that the Earth was [...] "round", his meaning was {{ambiguous}} and some writers think he referred to a disc-shaped Earth. However, other writings by Isidore {{make it clear that}} he considered the Earth to be globular. Indeed, the theory of a <b>spherical</b> <b>earth</b> had always been the prevailing assumption among the learned since at least Aristotle, who had divided the <b>spherical</b> <b>earth</b> into zones of climate, with a frigid clime at the poles, a deadly torrid clime near the equator, and a mild and habitable temperate clime between the two.|$|R
